/// eo9:net-l4-over-l2 — the TCP/IP middleware world (plan/09 Decision 18).
///
/// `net.l4.over-l2` is the layered-net design's payoff: a whole TCP/IP stack as
/// ordinary provider middleware. It imports the link layer (`eo9:net/l2` — whichever
/// provider is composed below it: `net.virtio` on metal, a mock in tests), the
/// monotonic clock (`eo9:time/time` — TCP retransmission and ARP timers), and entropy
/// (`eo9:entropy/entropy` — ephemeral ports and TCP initial sequence numbers), and
/// exports transport sockets (`eo9:net/l4`), so a program that imports only `l4`
/// gets working TCP and UDP by composition:
///
///   net.virtio $ net.l4.over-l2 $ program
///
/// There is no configure interface yet (adding one needs an `l4-over-l2-config`
/// interface in `wit/net`, recorded as a follow-up): the documented default addressing
/// is QEMU user-mode networking's layout — 10.0.2.15/24 with gateway 10.0.2.2 — bound
/// lazily on first use, so plain composition works and never traps (plan/09 D14).
package eo9:net-l4-over-l2@0.1.0;

world l4-over-l2 {
    import eo9:net/l2@0.1.0;
    import eo9:time/time@0.1.0;
    import eo9:entropy/entropy@0.1.0;

    export eo9:net/l4@0.1.0;
}
